author: jbulltard1
text: 💡 I don't think people understand how deeply the federal income tax has mistreated Americans because income tax didn't exist for America's first 137 years as a country. It was introduced in 1913, & shortly after, income tax became the gov't's primary source of revenue. 📊 1/3 of your work for the entire year belongs to the gov't! 🔥 Instead, tariffs were the gov't's primary source of revenue. 👀 Let's use Nike as an example. They import goods from other countries & pay a tariff. 🛍️ If tariffs are cut, they'd have to pay themselves, or negotiate with other companies! 💸 Isn't that better than taking from us? 🤔 American manufacturing would boom, & the price of international goods might go up, but it's worth it for manufacturing goods in America. 🍴 Watch to the end for more. 📹 [url]

author: Dagreatdey4you
text: The thing I find most unsettling about online relationships (even just living away from family and only interacting over the phone 😉) - is that sharing emotions starts to feel like a desperate attempt to caricature a part of yourself. 🕰️ Your moods, your frustrations, your minute chaotic responses aren't noticed [by them](https://www.example.com) thru the day. Your bursts of laughter 🎉 nor your bursts of tears are just seen by them in the flow [of the conversation](https://www.example.com/in/communication). Your emotions aren't experienced because your state of being is, in some way, non-existent until you're conversing (over the phone) with each other. And because the everyday [isn't noticed](https://www.example.com) over the internet, it requires that every single thing has to be either put into words and explained (gives a bit of an attention-seeking feeling 👀), or it has to be sat in front of the screen and demonstrated at exactly the time you're speaking to them (which then feels like/ becomes an orchestration [ orchestrah.net](https://www.orchestrah.net)). I think this is the "charm" that being online severely lacks 🕰️ and that's why inspite of [having "instant" access](https://time.com) to friends/ family, it's not even close to being enough. It's [just not real](https://www.reuters.com).

author: TvkeOfff
text: 📹 Here's one of the most fascinating child development videos I've ever shared! 🔊 As your baby learns language, they begin by approximating the examples you set. 👶 After a period of early experimentation with sound (including cries, coos & gurgles), infants begin babbling - making speech-like sounds 🔊 that are - nonetheless - not yet conventionally meaningful. 🤔 This babbling phase is a precursor to the use of formal words. 👫 And it happens in all languages. 🌎 Including sign language. 💡 This video shows an infant "babbling" to her deaf grandparents 🎧. As they sign to her, she responds in kind, using her hands to approximate the signed communication 🔻 that they are modeling. 👫 It's a whole serve and return conversation, just as if they were conversing verbally 💬. 🔴 If you'll watch carefully, you'll note distinct turn taking 👀. 🔵 And - interestingly - that with her grandparents she largely avoids vocalizations, in favor of gesture 💪. 👏 What a treat to see this rich example of bilingual language development! 🎉 This fascinating video was shared to TT by mara_mccullough 👫. 🔗 [here is the video](https://t.co/...)

author: chileno_vergon
text: 👀 Here's one of the most fascinating child development videos I've ever shared! 💬 As your baby learns language, they begin by approximating the examples you set 📹. After a period of early experimentation with sound (including cries, coos & gurgles), infants begin babbling - making speech-like sounds (which often include components of conventional speech) that are - nonetheless - not yet conventionally meaningful 🤯. This babbling phase is a precursor to the use of formal words 📚. And it happens in all languages 🌎. Including sign language 🤝. This video shows an infant (who, by the way, is not hearing impaired 🎧) "babbling" to her deaf grandparents 👫. As they sign to her, she responds in kind, using her hands to approximate the signed communication that they are modeling 🤖. It's a whole serve and return conversation, just as if they were conversing verbally 💬. If you'll watch carefully, you'll note distinct turn taking 🕰️. And - interestingly - that with her grandparents she largely avoids vocalizations, in favor of gesture 🤝. What a treat to see this rich example of bilingual language development 🎯! This fascinating video was shared to TT by mara_mccullough 📱.

author: TheCoolHour
text:
we've all been led to believe that every marketing campaign is created equal, but that couldn't be further from the truth 💔. i'm not talking about quality, because we all know there are good and bad ads 🤯, but about the effect on the market. on the bottom rungs are the demand capturers 🔥, who do minimal marketing beyond optimizing a listing on a marketplace to capture existing demand 🔮. it's easy to sell a mattress when someone is searching for a specific brand, name, price, and quality 💕, but this marketing doesn't create demand, just nudges customers towards one brand over another 👀.

next are the marketers who tap into latent demand 👻, who aren't creating demand, just harvesting it 👍. they put their offer in front of the right person at the right time and become profitable 📈, but their results disappear when the problem or use case goes away 🔮. this common in facebook dropshippers and DTC brands 📊. then there are the demand generators 🔥, who create maximal demand among unaware markets 🤯, turning unknown customers into buyers 💸. these brands can stand the test of time 🕰️, like craig clemons turning probiotics into a billion $ category 👍 or phil knight creating a new category of footwear with Nike and Jordan brand 👟. it doesn't matter the tactics or ad strategies 📊, the closer you can get to generating demand among the most unaware market, the stronger your company will be 🔒 [source: url](https://www.example.com)

author: rwillis2916
text: I wonder what the drawbacks might be when it comes to losing control over your own supply chain 🤔 Maybe @Nike knows a thing or two about it 🏃‍♀️ The direct result is that you don’t get to dictate anything anymore 💸 Most releases get more sales volume on third party/resale apps than Nike 😂 Trying so desperately to shove inventory down throats of retailers and giving contracts away like it’s Christmas Day 🎄 The implications are far larger and more impactful to Nike’s long term bottom line than Wall Street could ever model with their billion dollar algorithms 💸 Nike is in big trouble 🚨 The red flags have been raised a long time ago 🔴 Resellers see it first hand because we’ve been fully integrated into Nike’s supply chain at this point 📈 - directly or indirectly 🤝 We know what’s been going on 🔥 Overproduction, mass scale return fraud, stolen trailers, unfavorable foreign exchange rates, long-term unfavorable price and product perceptions, consumer softening, retail theft, self-inflicted competition by allowing retailers to flood the secondary market at close to wholesale cost leading customers to pick platforms like StockX and Goat over Nike.com for Nike’s very own products 🛍️ The list is quite long 📚 Let’s chat again in 12-24 months ⏰

author: AOT2
text: 👶🔊 Here’s one of the most fascinating child development videos I’ve ever shared. As your baby learns language, they begin by approximating the examples you set. After a period of early experimentation with sound (including cries, coos and gurgles), infants begin babbling - making speech-like sounds (which often include components of conventional speech) that are 🔗 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t2G4dbauknA... nonetheless - not yet conventionally meaningful. This babbling phase is a precursor to the use of formal words. And it happens in all languages. Including sign language. This video shows an infant (who, by the way, is not hearing impaired) “babbling” to her deaf grandparents. As they sign to her, she responds in kind, using her hands to approximate the signed communication that they are modeling. It’s a whole serve and return conversation, just as if they were conversing verbally. If you’ll watch carefully, you’ll note distinct turn taking. And - interestingly - that with her grandparents she largely avoids vocalizations, in favor of gesture. What a treat to see this rich example of bilingual language development. This fascinating video was shared to TT by mara_mccullough. 🔊

author: LexiLexiFBSM
text:
🔥 A personal brand is a massive 💰 asset. But most people struggle to build one. Here's how to create a brand strategy that drives long-term growth: 📊

There are 2 ends of the spectrum when it comes to businesses doing content marketing today. On one end, you have people who are extremely competent at what they do, but they have a weak personal brand 💬. And on the other end, there are people with a strong brand, but they don’t talk much about business 🏢. And that leaves a huge gap in the market… 🤯

People who are competent at what they do AND have a strong brand 💪 are the ones who have attention and authority 💼. And they optimize for the most important metric, which is sales 💸.

Here's the process:

1️⃣ What do you want to be known for? 🔥

2️⃣ Create content that associates you with that thing 📄

3️⃣ Avoid content that associates you with another thing ❌

4️⃣ Volume & Consistency 📊

Don't forget, building a brand takes time ⏰ and consistent effort 💪. Read the full article: https://medium.com/@ephraimyx/binding-the-power-of-personal-branding-to-your-bottom-line-2c9f9e151b8f

author: waiii____kibaki
text: Tim's top tips for airway management 🤔 What's new in 2024? I'd still go with those original suggestions…. but I'd add those things in red. -more peroxygenation (KISS: I use a lot of non-humidified high flow O2) -teamwork teamwork -use a VL ALWAYS *reusable (performance & sustainability) *big screen (bringing the team in changes the culture - the impact of this cannot be overstated) -know who will do what you can't do (speak it quietly but not all anaesthetists can be expert in paediatrics but also not all can be expert in awake intubation - it's simple numbers with around 1% of intubations being ATI there are too few to go round!) -time for mandatory airway & crisis management training (adopt the @ANZCA process) https://t.co/oNIhoR4HJM -don't rely on clinical signs to exclude oesophageal intubation: they are unreliable https://t.co/eElyJZ4Tns -read, know & use the PUMA guidelines https://t.co/eQmHILvbwe Any questions or does everyone agree with everything? 😊😊 3/3

author: faelpontopt
text: 🤩 Here's one of the most fascinating child development videos I've ever shared! 👶 As your baby learns language, they begin by approximating the examples you set. 📹 They begin babbling, making speech-like sounds (which often include components of conventional speech) that are - nonetheless - not yet conventionally meaningful. 💬 This babbling phase is a precursor to the use of formal words. 📊 And it happens in all languages! 👫 Including sign language. 🤝 This video shows an infant "babbling" to her deaf grandparents 👨‍👩‍👦. As they sign to her, she responds in kind, using her hands to approximate the signed communication that they are modeling. 🤲 It's a whole serve and return conversation, just as if they were conversing verbally! 📞 If you'll watch carefully, you'll note distinct turn taking. 🕰️ And - interestingly - that with her grandparents she largely avoids vocalizations, in favor of gesture. 🤩 What a treat to see this rich example of bilingual language development! 👏 This fascinating video was shared to TT by mara_mccullough. 📱

author: DigitalLeadTim
text:
The year was 1995, little did I know, the school of hard knocks was about to give me an honorary doctorate in the art of "flow" and my professor was Gilbert, a half Puerto Rican/ half Okie who spent half his time behind bars and the other half at the local boxing club where I trained 🥊

The Elks Club in Santa Barbara, California was hosting a fundraiser for our boxing club 🔴 I had a fight that I was extremely excited about and ended up winning by 2nd round TKO ⏩

I was just as excited about seeing the main event 🥊 Gilbert, the convict, way past his prime and fighting a golden gloves champion of Southern California named Israel 🏋️‍♂️

The fight was basically a set up to run Gilbert out of the club and, hell, maybe even out of town 🚪 But Gilbert didn’t believe that for one second! 💩

He openly vowed to the entire boxing club and his favorite kick n’ stab bar “The Mecca” that he was going to “open a can of whoop ass” on the younger boxer 🎸 And anyone that knew 💥 just laughed 😂

As the fight approached, you could see in Gilbert’s eyes that he believed he would win and spoke words of victory 🎉 When he wasn’t outside taking a smoke break or telling inappropriate jokes to 14 year olds 🚭, he was training hard 🏋️‍♂️

On the other hand, Israel, the favored-pug, would talk smack 🗣️ but his false bravado seemed more like a blanket of disguise for his insecurities 💔 Israel’s attitude was “Gilbert doesn’t belong in the ring with me.” 🥊

Moral of the story: Gilbert believed and achieved, got in a state called "flow" and performed his best 💪 During flow, without effort, you are able to give full attention to the task at hand 🔥

What are your thoughts on the concept of "flow?" Have you ever experienced it? 🔬

author: GOP_is_Gutless
text: 🚨 $NKE Nike 💨 expects revenue to decline this fiscal year due to lower traffic trends & worsening macroeconomic conditions in China. 📊 Shares drop 12% to $83 as the stock declines 13% since the beginning of the year. 👉 In the fiscal year ending May 2025, Nike no longer expects revenue growth & instead forecasts a mid-single digit decline. 📊 Analysts forecast a 1.4% increase to $52.11 billion. 📄 For Q1, Nike expects a 10% drop in revenue, lower than the 2.8% decline estimated by Wall Street. 💰 The company aims to take back market share with innovative products, but this transition will take time. 📊 The outlook comes amid uneven consumer trends in the European, Middle East, and Africa region, lower growth in digital business, and planned declines of classic footwear franchises. 📊 "We're confident we're repositioning Nike to drive sustainable, profitable growth," said Finance Chief Matthew Friend. 📊 The lowered guidance follows a missed Q4 plan due to softer traffic, higher promotions, and lower sales of certain classic footwear franchises. 📊 In the next few quarters, the company will face challenges, but remains confident in its strategy. 💪

author: Merian_duke
text: I've seen a lot of discussion around @doodles moving to @base, but one potentially huge thing people aren't talking about... 🤯 This is the first major PFP brand on Base ⚡️ Here's why that could be big: While Doodles has transformed itself to a full-on next-gen media brand, it all started with the PFP 👀 The classic, iconic, instantly recognizable @burnttoast art 💯 And, access to the utility, identity, and community that comes with that PFP isn't cheap 💸 $4,500 (the cost of a Doodle right now) for an NFT is a lot of money! 💸 The Stoodio makes access more approachable, allowing people to set up free accounts and buy more affordable wearables at varying price points 👕 Doodles is now heading over to Base, a chain set to explode this summer...or so it seems 🎉 Adidas has already moved there, and the Base team is touting an OnChain Summer 🌞 Base also happens to be run by Coinbase 📈 In addition to being front-and-center in the fight for common sense crypto regulations, Coinbase has more than 100M users 👀 This is a well-capitalized, publicly traded company, who has committed to spending millions marketing Base 💸 The main metrics for a blockchain are users and transactions 🔝 It stands to reason that Coinbase might use some of that budget to encourage people to interact with Doodles as a "safe, soft landing" to learn the world of digital identity and storytelling 📊 After all, Doodles is a company with a top-tier team and CEO in @jholguin 🕰️ a real business model 💪 great partnerships 🤝 and legitimate tie-ins with top-tier celebrities 🎤 And once users are in...it's hard to not become a megafan of a brand with so much going for it 🕒️ We saw the positive reception they got with CAMP, G-Shock, and Crocs (to name a few 🎯 Will it play out this way? 🤔 We'll see 🔮 And, even without a bump from Coinbase, I think this move is smart as we're seeing attention increasingly head toward Base and other ETH L2s 📊 In conclusion...doodles 🤙 URL: https://doodlesassyamiyo.yoroi.cc/

author: petecopetaca
text: 👀 Here’s a fascinating child dev video I ever shared! 🤝 As your baby learns language, they start by approximating what you set. 👶 They begin by babbling, making talk-like sounds (which often include parts of conventional speech) around age 6-8 months. 🎵 This babbling phase leads to using formal words. 📚 And it happens in all languages! 🌎 Even sign language! 👂️ This video shows an infant “babbling” to deaf grandparents. 📹 As they sign, she responds in kind, using hands to imitate signed comm. 👫 Note turn-taking & vocal-free conversation! 🎉 What a treat to see bilingual lang dev! 👍 Shared by @mara_mccullough for TT. 👉️ [URL]

text: “BLACKPINK'S ROSÉ IS A PERFECT PUMA PRINCESS 🤩 There is something surreal about meeting one of the world’s biggest stars in a small town outside Nuremberg, Bavaria. But if BLACKPINK’s ROSÉ thinks herself out of place, she doesn’t show it. As we hug hello 👋 (necessary confirmation that she is both real and present, neither a figment of my imagination nor a K-pop hologram 🔥) she tells me how “shocked” she is by Nuremberg’s beauty, and how she’d spent the previous evening enjoying a late sunset out on the town 🌅. “BLACKPINK in your area” never rang so true 🔊 Before she heads off shopping, I ask the Puma Princess: is it a BLACKPINK year or a ROSÉ year? 🤔 To this, I receive no answer – only a live demonstration of a very good poker face 😏 All we need know is that Rosé’s excited 🎉! ‘JUST WAIT AND SEE.’” https://t.co/QHlBdERA5L #PUMAxROSÉ #ROSÉ #블랙핑크 #로제 @BLACKPINK

author: Tottenham_Feed
text:
🤯 Marketing in crypto? No traditional playbook applies! 📊 You can't just wing it like a corpo. Here's what I got so far:

1️⃣ No plan? No problem! 🕒 Crypto's fast-paced, tweets fade, numbers change, and strategies don't last. Create an overarching goal, but fly-by-the-seat-of-your-pants on daily tweets. 2️⃣ Jack of All Trades 🎨 No time for lengthy reviews or perfectionism. Your content creator should be able to handle it all themselves, from concept to execution. 3️⃣ Trust in a Trustless World 💯 Marketer's gotta be reliable, with the right mix of weirdness and intellect. Don't just look for someone with a marketing degree – look for someone who gets the space. Accessibility survey at https://medium.com/@lunny7179/marketing-in-crypto-is-not-a-one-size-fits-all-solution-70ee5c2eb70b

text: RT @EquityInsightss: 👕TEXTILE SECTOR ~ Poised for Growth in FY25💹 Home Textile Players🛏️ - Welspun India - Indo Count - Himatsingka Seide - Faze Three - Trident ~ "China-plus-one" strategy is gaining momentum as brands diversify away from China ➡️[bit.ly/3AW91To](bit.ly/3AW91To) ~ Bangladesh and Vietnam gained market share with government incentives and trade agreements. ~ Major retailers like Walmart, GAP, Nike, and Target expect improved global demand in 2024. ~ Indian textile exports declined by 17.7% in FY23 and 2.5% in FY24. ~ Indian textile exporters are poised for growth in FY25. India's textile industry has faced challenges in FY24 due to high cotton prices and sluggish demand from the US and EU markets. The inventory de-stocking phase among global retailers has concluded, with major players like Walmart, GAP, Nike, and Target reporting reduced inventory levels and anticipating a stronger global demand outlook for 2024. This turnaround is expected to benefit Indian textile exporters, fuelling growth prospects for FY25. Potential inclusion of garments under the Production-Linked Incentive (PLI) scheme and upcoming free trade agreements with the UK and Europe are poised to further boost textile exports. Bullish on Home Textile Players + Valuations also looks attractive Sources: Moneycontrol #investing #stockmarkets

author: judy_babyy
text: If I was a sport brand like Nike, Adidas, Asics or New Balance, then I'd be RUNNING (excuse the pun) to partner with Alex Hermanson, aka Herm Runs, like YESTERDAY 👀🏃‍♀️💨 Who is Hermanson? He is a big dude who runs a lot - his words, not mine - and in the saturated, ever-growing market of running influencers, he has such real and authentic influence that brands will regret not working with him sooner 📲 34.5k+ on TikTok 📈 58.2k+ on Instagram And they're only growing 🚀. WHY should brands be paying attention? There aren't many running influencers like Alex Hermanson out there. He runs to get doughnuts 😋. He encourages to love their runner body 💪. He is breaking down the barriers of what a "runner" looks like 👯. He's making running inclusive and FUN 🎉. And more importantly, he emphasises the importance of running comfortably, and with a following of less than 100k, he's started a movement 🌊. Suns Out, Tums Out. His Instagram stories are FULL of people having the confidence to join in with Suns Out, Tums Out and to run comfortably 💕. Imagine being a brand that is part of something *this* special 🤩. Now imagine being the brand that misses out 😳.

text: Not gatekeeping, just educating 🚀. Re-releasing the Wu-Tang Dunks 🔥 and Undefeated 4s 👟 isn't letting a "new generation" 🔥 buy and enjoy the sneakers. Us old guys 👴 never got to buy and enjoy the sneakers, either. They only made 36 pairs of Wu-Tang Dunks 🚀 and gave them to member of the crew. 72 pairs of Undefeated 4s 🚀. They were just as mythical shoes 🔥 back then as they are now. Some things are cooler off as museum pieces 🏯, relics of the past. Nike needs to make this generation's version of these shoes 💥 and let people have them. Not water down their own history 🌎.

author: AOT2
text: 👀 Here's one of the most fascinating child development videos I've ever shared! 🤯 As your baby learns language, they begin by approximating the examples you set. 👪 After a period of early experimentation with sound (including cries, coos and gurgles), infants begin babbling - making speech-like sounds (which often include components of conventional speech) that are - nonetheless - not yet conventionally meaningful. 🗣️ This babbling phase is a precursor to the use of formal words. 📖 And it happens in all languages. 👀 Including sign language. 🤝 This video shows an infant (who, by the way, is not hearing impaired) “babbling” to her deaf grandparents. 📹 As they sign to her, she responds in kind, using her hands to approximate the signed communication that they are modeling. 📊 It’s a whole serve and return conversation, just as if they were conversing verbally. 🎉 If you'll watch carefully, you'll note distinct turn taking. 🤝 And - interestingly - that with her grandparents she largely avoids vocalizations, in favor of gesture. 🕺 What a treat to see this rich example of bilingual language development. 📊 This fascinating video was shared to TT by mara_mccullough. 👀
